The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, June 17, 2004 				 Britain offers transit help
 A STAFF REPORTER																								A three-member team, led by Paul Walsh of the British deputy high commission, on Wednesday met transport minister Subhas Chakraborty at Writers Buildings and expressed its keeness to be involved in plans to modernise Calcuttas mass transport.																								According to officials, the British team was keen on building the proposed Light Rail Transit System (tramcars on elevated tracks). The governments plans envision operating about half-a-dozen coaches on an elevated path on a stretch between Thakurpukur and Barrackpore.																								An Indo-British consortium has offered to build the system. The consortium comprises one Indian and four British companies, all engaged in implementing modern transport projects. 																								Earlier two companies  one from Denmark and another from Japan  had offered to be involved in the project.
